The speedy march and intrepid attack of the Chersonites, by divert- ing the attention of the Goths, affisted the operations of the Impe- rial generals. The Goths, vanquished on every fide, were driven into the mountains‚ where, in the course of a severe campaign, above an hundred thousand were computed to have perished by cold and hunger. Peace was at length granted to their humble supplica- tions; the eldest son of Araric was accepted as the most valuable liostage3 and Constantine endeavoured to convince their chiefs, by a liberal distribution of honours and rewards, how far the friendship of the Romans was preferable to their enmity.
